 the expense of Indigenous peoples and other marginalized communities. But over the past two decades, these marginalized populations have increasingly turned to participatory mapping practices to develop new, innovative maps that reassert local concepts of place and space, thus harnessing the power of cartography in their struggles for justice. In twelve essays written by community leaders, activists, and scholars, Radical Cartographies critically explores the ways in which participatory mapping is being used by Indigenous, Afro-descendant, and other traditional groups in Latin America to preserve their territories and cultural identities. Through this pioneering volume, the authors fundamentally rethink the role of maps, with significant lessons for marginalized communities across the globe, and launch a unique dialogue about the radical edge of a new social cartography.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aCartographyxSocial aspectszLatin America. 0aCommunitieszLatin America. 0aEthnosociology. 0aHuman geographyzLatin America. 0aIndigenous peopleszLatin AmericaxEthnic identity. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aBryan, Joe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBryan, Joe, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCruz, Melquiades, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Almeida Farias, Emmanuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Almeida, Alfredo Wagner Berno, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGonzález, Carlos Alberto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHale, Charles R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHale, Charles, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLamiña,